│ The user wants me to fix a crash in the LLVM `loop-vectorize` pass.                                                                                                                      │
│ The crash is an assertion failure in `ScalarEvolution::isLoopEntryGuardedByCond`: `Assertion 'isAvailableAtLoopEntry(LHS, L) && "LHS is not available at Loop Entry"' failed.`           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Here's my analysis of the problem:                                                                                                                                                       │
│ 1.  The provided LLVM IR contains two loops, `%loop.1` and `%loop.2`.                                                                                                                    │
│ 2.  The backedge-taken count of `%loop.2` depends on a value `%add.1` computed inside `%loop.1`. This value is passed to `%loop.2` via a PHI node `%add.lcssa` in the exit block of      │
│ `%loop.1`.                                                                                                                                                                               │
│ 3.  The `loop-vectorize` pass is run on the function. It identifies loops to vectorize and processes them. In this case, it will first process and vectorize `%loop.1`.                  │
│ 4.  Vectorizing `%loop.1` significantly transforms its body. The original instruction `%add.1` is removed and replaced by vector operations.                                             │
│ 5.  This transformation invalidates the Scalar Evolution (SCEV) information for any expression that depends on `%add.1`. Specifically, the SCEV expression for the backedge-taken count  │
│ of `%loop.2` becomes stale.                                                                                                                                                              │
│ 6.  The `LoopVectorizePass` then proceeds to analyze `%loop.2`. When it tries to compute the trip count for `%loop.2`, it uses the stale SCEV information. This leads to querying SCEV   │
│ with an expression (`%add.1`) that is no longer available at the entry of `%loop.2`, causing the assertion failure.                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The fix is to ensure that after a loop is vectorized, any analysis information that might have been invalidated by the transformation is cleared. The `LoopVectorizePass` already has a  │
│ mechanism for this: it uses `AnalysisManager::invalidate`. However, it seems to be missing an invalidation call after successfully vectorizing a loop.                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `LoopVectorizePass::processLoop` function in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp` is where the vectorization of a single loop happens. After the loop is transformed    │
│ (the `if (HasVPlan)` block), we need to tell the analysis manager that the function has been modified. This will cause analyses like Scalar Evolution to be re-run when next requested,  │
│ ensuring they operate on up-to-date information.                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The correct way to do this is to call `FAM.invalidate<ScalarEvolutionAnalysis>(F)` after the transformation. However, a more robust approach is to invalidate all function analyses, as  │
│ vectorization can have wide-ranging effects. The pass manager provides a way to do this by returning `PreservedAnalyses::none()` from the pass's `run` method. Since `processLoop` is    │
│ called within `runImpl`, and we want to continue processing other loops, we can't just return. Instead, we can use `FAM.invalidate(F, PreservedAnalyses::none())`. This will clear all   │
│ function-level analyses, forcing them to be recomputed for subsequent loops.                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will add `FAM.invalidate(F, PreservedAnalyses::none());` inside `LoopVectorizePass::processLoop` right after the code block that performs the vectorization transformation. This will  │
│ ensure that when the pass moves on to `%loop.2`, it will get fresh analysis results.                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '10631a\                                                                                                                                                                          │
│       // Invalidate all analyses, since the vectorizer might have changed\                                                                                                               │
│       // the CFG.\                                                                                                                                                                       │
│       FAM.invalidate(F, PreservedAnalyses::none());' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                                                                     │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
